<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Briefing Note 2012</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:20pt; margin:4pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:20pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Combined Heat and Power Association (HOT50)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Combined Heat and Power Association (CHPA) welcomes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the opportunity to provide written evidence to the Energy and Climate Change Committee’s inquiry on heat. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHPA</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is the leading advocate </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an integrated approach to delivering energy services using combined heat and power and district heating and cooli</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ng.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The CHPA’s response sets out key elements of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">sector </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and highlights immediate issues where policy focus would be of value. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">would also welcome the opportunity to provide oral evidence to the Committee. </span></p><h1 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></h1><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Heat, </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">unlike</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> power, </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is an intrinsically local issue and is not a standardised commodity. Central to understanding heat </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">decarbonisation </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is appreciating that heat</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (and c</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ooling) requirements vary hugely</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> by user</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Understanding the user’s need first is therefore key to cost-</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">effective </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">decarbonisation. </span></li><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">With </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an increased </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">use of electricity</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> including </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat and transport, there is a pressing need to consider how different energy needs interact. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Without </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an integrated energy policy</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">considering heat and power</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> together</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, the</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> UK risks </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">creating a very expensive, </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">inefficient energy system.</span></li><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Decarbonising industrial heat is one of </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">our </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">most difficult challenges. In the short to medium term, the need </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">focus on increased efficiency, </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">including </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">through the deployment of CHP</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> will be </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">key to </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">keeping businesses </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">competitive whilst reducing emissions. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Key to increasing deployment of CHP will be</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Provide e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">xpress financial provision for the new CHP policy, currently under development, is necessary</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">; and,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Address </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">removal of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Levy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">xemption </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ertificates, a 2013 tax rise which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">significantly affecting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">operators. F</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ull relief from the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Carbon Price Support</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> help the Government meet its original commitments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul></ul></ul><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">high density</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> areas, Government has identified heat networks </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">as </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">best way to meet </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">needs of householders, business</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">es</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and the public sector. The </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">creation </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of the </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eat </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">N</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">etworks </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">D</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">elivery </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">U</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">nit is a welcome step forward. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">F</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">urther policies </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are needed </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to stimulate </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat network</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> investment</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, including</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Provide</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> RHI funding for</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">deployment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of renewable</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Encourage</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the recovery of waste heat to heat networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Ensure</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> local authorities retain legal powers to encourage heat networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 41.25pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Create </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">long term investment fra</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">meworks for heat infrastructure.</span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><h1 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Growing recognition of </span><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">heat’s importance</span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Accounting for half of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> energy demand, h</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eat is central to the energy debate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">If we are t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">o achieve our decarbonisation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">commitments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">reducing emissions from heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">be at the heart of energy policy.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DECC’s creatio</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n of a heat directorate in 2011, and the publication of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">trateg</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">201</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">2 and 201</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">3 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">demonstrates </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s growing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">recogni</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the importance of heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Heat policy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">must focus on the needs of the consumer</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">While p</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ower is a standardised commodity</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> heat is highly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to the consumer</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s requirements</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">For example, h</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">omes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and offices </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">need low-temperature heat for heating and hot water</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, while</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ndustries need high temperature heat for industrial processes. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The difficulty </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of transporting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">over long</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> distances ensures heat generation is always </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">generated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, therefore,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">involves a close relationship with the final </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">user</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">policy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, therefore,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> requires</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> a more</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> decentralised</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">user</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-orientated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">With </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">such an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">approach, it becomes clear that there </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is no </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">one </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">solution for decarbonising </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Rather </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">suite of technologies </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is needed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">each</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> tailored to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">specific users’ </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">needs.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">An integrated systems approach controls costs for consumers</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">With an increased use of elec</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tricity for energy needs, including heat and transport, there is a pressing need to consider how different energy needs interact. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The 2013 Heat Strategy recognises the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">energy system’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">complex nature and recognises that a more cost-effective system will ari</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">se when all energy uses are better integrated.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">By using tools such as thermal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">stores, a more integrated energy system </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">help reduce overall costs by better managing electricity demand and supply</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Without considering heat and power </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">together</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, the UK risks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> creating a very expensive, inefficient energy system.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Energy efficiency links key </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">options </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">for decarbonising</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> heat</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">here are many technologies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> can offer low carbon heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">including generation technologies like </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat pumps, solar</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> thermal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">combined heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and power (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">hatever generation solution is deployed, energy efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">across generation, delivery </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">infrastructure, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and final demand</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is key</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><h1 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Industrial heat </span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Currently,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he high temperatures required by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">industrial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">processes </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">mostly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ed by individual gas-fired boilers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> or CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, but with an increasing role for bio</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">energy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he relatively high cost of electricity makes it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">prohibitively </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">expensive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for widespread </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">industrial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat generation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Electrically</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-generated heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">needed for some </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">processes such as iron and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">aluminium</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> smelting</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> where the high temperatures required cannot be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">readily </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">achieved by other means</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Energy efficiency sits at the heart of industrial heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">decarbonisation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">or medium temperature industrial heat needs, fossil and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">bioenergy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> will remain the key sources for cost-effective heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in the medium term</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">But these</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> energy options pose challenges as well. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">biomass sup</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ply chain is immature</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">creat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">security of supply concerns for industry. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Users</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ossil fuel</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are exposed </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to price volatility</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Carbon </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">apture and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">torage remains a future option, but is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">too expensive for industry in the medium term.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A focus on energy efficiency is therefore vital to reduce emissions from industrial heat. The key </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">technolog</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y that is underexploited in UK industry remains combined heat and power</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> which delivers a reductio</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n in fuel use of up to 30%</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Combined Heat and Power</span></h3><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ombined heat and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> power (CHP)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is sourced from gas, biomass, biogas and energy from waste.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">As an energy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">efficiency technology, CHP rec</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">onciles major issues including</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Carbon reduction, saving 15 million tonnes of CO</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> annually.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Cost-effectiveness, </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">recognised </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">by</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Government </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">as one of the most effective forms of carbon reduction</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Security of </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">upply, reducing gas imports by 5% annually. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 16.7pt; padding-left:11.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Industrial competitiveness, by reducing</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a site’s energy use, and therefore costs, by </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">up to 30%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Please see the </span><a href="http://www.chpa.co.uk/medialibrary/2013/01/31/6c93a612/CHPA%20Expression%20of%20Interest%20to%20Committee%20Inquiry%20on%20Gas%20Generation%20Strategy.pdf"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">CHPA’s response to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Energy and Climate Change </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Committee’s Gas Generation Strategy inquiry</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">more detail on CHP benefits.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DECC Heat Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">makes the case</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> for</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> targeted </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">support </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">for new </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">gas CHP </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DECC estimates an economic potential for more than 18 GW of CHP in the UK, almost triple current capacity. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he Heat Strategy recognised that gas CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> requires </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">policy mechanism </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for it to achieve its potential </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in decarbonising the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">UK energy system. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">therefore made </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the welcome </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">commit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">develo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a bespoke </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">gas fired </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP policy to support </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">deployment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> members are</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">closely </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">with DECC on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">analysis </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">policy options</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> for its ‘bespoke policy’. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Industry </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">regards </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">options to either incentivise</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> CHP </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the energ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y savings it delivers, or a feed-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in tariff for efficiently generated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP-produced electricity heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">having </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">greatest potential.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">he </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Government has not yet committed a dedicate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">d budget </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">its </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">bespoke CHP policy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. This lack of financial commitment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">must</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> be addressed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> to ensure investor confidence is created</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">xisting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">gas </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">capacity</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">faces challenges</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">proposed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">policy is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">specifically </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">limited </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to supporting new CHP capacity, and does not recognise </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the Government’s £</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">0m</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to £165m annual</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> tax rise</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> on CHP operators </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">created </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">by the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">early</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> removal of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP’s LEC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">At the time of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">LECs </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">decision, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he Government </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">indicated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a solution would be found, but n</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">o action </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">was taken </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to return this value to existing CHP operators</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The impact of this decision, which was implemented in April 2013, is now starting to hit British industry and undermine the competitiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> sites</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Some CHP </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">operators </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are reducing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eir </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHP </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">generation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">because, with the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">removal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of LECs and the addition of Carbon Price Support, it is no longer economical to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">operate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Damaged investor confidence limits new</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> CHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> investment</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">uch of the expected investment for new CHP installations will likely come from those companies which operate existing CHP. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The CHPA is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> aware of a number of companies who </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are hesitant </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to invest in CHP again because of the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">decision </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to remove </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">LEC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">E.ON</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> has stated that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the removal of LECs has not given “much encouragement to take further investment”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">If investors attach higher risks to CHP projects, it will raise </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the cost to industry, business and taxpayers. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Support investment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ompetitiveness</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> with Carbon </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">rice </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">upport relief </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">o address the twin concerns of investor confidence and existing CHP operation, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">here is a need for DECC to urgently consider</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> returning the value lost to CHP operators from the removal of LECs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">A simple, direct way to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">restore investor confidence </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> to give CHP plant relief </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Carbon Price Support</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> equal </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">value </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">the LECs, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">helping </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">the Government to meet its</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">original </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2011 commitment.</span></p><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Renewable heat</span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Current support levels for renewable CHP-generated heat appears to be sufficient to bring forward new investment, but the Government </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">not introduce</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> a mechanism to allow investors to ‘lock in’ the value of the RHI payments when </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">investments </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">reach financi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">al close.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Without </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">such a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">mechanism, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">called </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Enhanced</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Preliminary Accreditation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">more than £1.5 billion in renewable CHP investments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> are ‘very unlikely’ to come forward</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, according to a survey of CHPA members. </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">RHI </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">needs an enhanced preliminary accreditat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ion scheme as a matter of urgency if </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">large-scale renewable investments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> are not to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">put </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">at </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">risk. </span></p><h1 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Recoverable heat</span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">High-temperature heat, as used by industry</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> or power stations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, can often be re-used for low-temperature demands, such as housing. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Either on t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he same site or via a network, proce</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">sses requiring high temperature heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> can pass lower temperature ‘waste’ heat to a secondary user.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">More than half of energy wasted in power generation</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Power generation wastes most of its heat through cooling towers, losing valuable efficiency and savings, and even the most efficient gas power plants </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">waste </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">half</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of the energy they consume</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">CHPA analysis found p</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ower stations waste more energy from their coo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ling towers than the total</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> UK</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">gas </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">demand for heating</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Across Europe, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the amount of waste heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">from thermal power generation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> substantial. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">One academic study estimates </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">waste heat from thermal generation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">add</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">up to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">nearly 2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,000</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Wh </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">annually</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (enough to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">mee</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">total </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat demand two and a half </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">times over)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, with o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">nly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">17% </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">that energy captured and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">recycled.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Challenge of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> link</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> industrial heat to demand</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Despite improving the efficiency of industrial processes, reducing and reusing waste products, there is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">often low temperature heat (below 100°C) which has no further industrial application.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Total </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">potential recoverable industrial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in Europe </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is estimated at over </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">580 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Wh </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">annually</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, or about 80% of total UK heat demand</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">integrated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">energy system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, this w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">aste heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> from power production and industry</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> can be supplied to a community heat network for local homes, public and commercial buildings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> at low cost and zero carbon, as occurs in Dunkirk</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, France</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Crucially, Dunkirk’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">scheme design was </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">championed by</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">cit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">leaders</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ithout </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">coordination, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">waste heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">opportunities are lost</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">For example, w</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e are aware of UK </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">cases where</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">housing developers install individual gas boilers rather t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">han access</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> available waste heat from local industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">R</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ecoverable heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">assessment welcome, but coordination is key</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We welcome </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DECC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’s commitment to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">assess the technical and economic potential for re-use of recovered hea</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t and to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">explore incentives for use </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of recoverable</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> heat. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, there are a number of institutional challen</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ges to linking this heat to demand. Recovering waste heat requires partnerships which do not naturally or currently exist between industry, local authorities, and housing developers. </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The development of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">a waste heat incentive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">, alongside increased coordinat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ion,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">necessary to exploit </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">this potentially valuable resource</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">More ambition needed for industrial steam networks policy</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Aggregating industrial energy users into </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">clusters </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">can allow steam </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">networks to serve multiple sites</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> increas</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> efficiency and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">compet</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">itiveness</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Vitally, i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ndustrial clusters would allow future carbon capture and storage </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">(CCS) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">infrastructure to be concentrated at </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> sites with costs shared among several users. These industrial clusters may also serve to attract new industry through reduc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ed energy costs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">he Heat Strategy notes the industrial clustering opportunity, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">but </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">unfortunately </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">does not propose </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">how to develop this policy further. </span></p><h1 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Domestic, commercial and public sector heat </span></h1><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ouseholders, businesses and public sector organisations </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">need affordable heating, hot water and, increasingly, cooling</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in commercial buildings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Currently, individual gas-fired boilers predominate but this will need to evolve as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">villages, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">towns and cities decarbonise.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">For lower density areas</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">individual heating so</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lutions are more appropriate. The starting point should be considering </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">building efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and then</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> generation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> technologies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> including </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">individual </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">microCHP</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (gas, LPG and eventually biogas) and wood boilers. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Large public sector and commercial bui</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ldings are increasingly turning to small-scale CHP, which allow them to save carbon and reduce waste. The number of CHP schemes below 10MW increased nearly 50% in the last four years, from 1,257 in 2008 to 1,860 in 2012.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> An example is the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> 1.1MW CHP plant </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">installed in Birmingham Heartlands Hospital in June 2008 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">saves £650,000 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">annually </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and reduces CO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> emissions by 8,000 tonnes per year. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">High density urban areas are characterised by space restrictions and high land values</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Air quality and noise </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">regulations limit the suitability of individual solutions such as heat pumps or biomass boilers.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">igher densities, however, make community solutions servicing households, commercial and public sector buildings potentially more cost-effective than individua</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">l ones.</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#9e0927; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">District heating and cooling</span></h3><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whilst it is vital to seek to reduce heat demand, it is also critical to look at the efficiency of heat supply. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Heat networks </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are pipe infrastructure that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">deliver heating or cooling</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> generated communally</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to homes and b</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">usinesses, rather than generating heat </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">individual properties</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">network</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> infrastructure facilitates gains in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> economies of scale </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in heat generation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">efficient, flexible and easily upgradeable.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eat networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> can </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">incorporate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a range of different </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at sources</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">heat pumps, solar thermal, boilers (both renewable and fossil fuelled), CHP (both renewable and fossil fuelled), geothermal, waste heat or energy from waste – some </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">options </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of which cannot be harnessed at an individual building level. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Benefits of district heating to consumers</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he UK Committee on Climate Change </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">recognises</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> district heating, using </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">low carbon generation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> or waste heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in high density area</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">one of the most cost effective </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">forms of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">carbon abatement</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">academic </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">studies have</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> found </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in urban areas, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">district hea</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ting is a cheaper solution </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">than</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">other options</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">This cost effectiveness means a lower cost for consumers and taxpayers. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whether serving public or private rented sector or </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">owner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">occupiers district heating</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is steadily growing, in cities like London, Sheffield and Nottingham, saving carbon </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> combat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> fuel poverty.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Heat networks </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">remove</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the need for the property owner to maintain, and ultimately replace, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">boiler.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Industry protecting consumers with proposals for independent regulation </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Recognising that heat customers should be afforded protection of comparable levels to those in the regulated gas and electricity sectors</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the CHPA, on behalf of the district heating i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ndustry, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> facilitating the development of an Independent Heat Customer Protection scheme for domestic and micro-business customers. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n independent steering committee, with representatives from consumer groups, government and the district heating industry</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are developing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">proposals</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and after </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">public consultation, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">aim to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">establish </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> scheme in 2014.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Government’s Heat Strategy ruled out regulation for heat networks and announced that Government “will seek to endorse an industry-led consumer protection schem</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e”. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DECC’s support will be a critical component of the Independent Heat Customer Protection scheme’s success.</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Participation in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">customer protection </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">scheme should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">be a condition for local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">to receive </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">support from HNDU and other </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Gov</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ernment recognises key role of local authorities</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Local authorities are central to the development of new district heating networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, acting</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> as brokers between key agencies, owning critical heat demand</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> through Planning and street works permissions. Deve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lopers are unlikely to risk initiating city-wid</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e schemes, so local authorities’ </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">long</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">term strategic view of heat, developing heat masterplans to facilitate interconnected networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, are important</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">welcome the commitment to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">launch the Heat Netwo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rk Delivery Unit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (HNDU)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">hand-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">holding</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> service for local authorities.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However, we have outlined four other key measures which would help </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">sti</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">mulate heat network development, both in the short term and long term, below.</span></p><h3 style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">1. Help</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> h</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">eat networks attract </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">long-term investment funding</span></h3><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Once the development stages of a project have been undertaken and a project is deemed viable, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">it may still be difficult </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to secure adequate funding at appropriate interest rates. Whilst the low but steady returns a heat network </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">can deliver are well suited to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">low-risk </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">investors such as pension fund</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">district heating schemes can be too small to meet </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">these funds</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">minimum investment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">thresholds.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">A national fund, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">as proposed under Allowable Solutions, would provide </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">professionally-managed concentration of capital</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> at a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> suitable sca</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">le for cost-effective, community-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">scale schemes such as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">heat networks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. </span></p><h3 style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2. Support </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">d</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">istrict heating and co</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">oling </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">directly</span></h3><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">While district heating is eligible under two targeted householder carbon reduction schemes, it does not currently receive any bespoke support from Government. </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Government </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">should consider ways to encourage renewable district heating, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">potentially including </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">upport</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> renewable district heating under the renewable heat incentive after its 2014 review</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Use </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">planning requirements </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">to drive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> district heating investments</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Planning requirements are currently driving deployment of net</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">works in new build developments, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">initiated schemes in social housing blocks</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">city-centre developments </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">encompassing a diverse mix of buildings.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Unfortunately these planning-led carbon emission investments are being undermined </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">unambitious</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> targets under Part L of the 2014 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and the proposed removal of the Planning and Energy Act 2008.</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">It is important that these important </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">planning </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">levers are retained. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4. Develop </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">wider, longer-term </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">vision</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">future heat networks</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Gover</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">nment’s Heat Strategy recognised the role of district heating as a route to decarbonise heat where suitable heat density exists. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DECC </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">modelling estimates </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an economic </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">20% of domestic heating and hot water demand met by heat networks in 2030</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">District heat scheme investments are made on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">0-year timetables,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> if the Government’s aim to significantly expand the amount of heat delivered through networks is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">realised</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, it will require a step change in deployment levels and more long-term thin</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">king.</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#9e0927; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-top-color:#9e0927; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Government </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">needs </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">lay out its long-term vision a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">nd policy for district heating.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:120%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt"> DECC,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt"> 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Future of Heating: Meeting the challenge</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt"> DECC, 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Future of Hea